<li id="cite_note-17"><b><a href="#cite_ref-17" title="">^</a></b> Collier, J.G. (2001) <a href="http://assets.cambridge.org/052178/2600/sample/0521782600ws.pdf" class="external text" title="http://assets.cambridge.org/052178/2600/sample/0521782600ws.pdf" rel="nofollow"><i>Conflict of Laws (Third edition)</i></a>(pdf) <a href="/wiki/Cambridge_University_Press" title="Cambridge University Press">Cambridge University Press</a>. "For the purposes of the English <a href="/wiki/Conflict_of_laws" title="Conflict of laws">conflict of laws</a>, every country in the world which is not part of <a href="/wiki/England_and_Wales" title="England and Wales">England and Wales</a> is a foreign country and its foreign laws. This means that not only totally foreign independent countries such as <a href="/wiki/France" title="France">France</a> or <a href="/wiki/Russia" title="Russia">Russia</a>... are foreign countries but also <a href="/wiki/British_Colonies" title="British Colonies" class="mw-redirect">British Colonies</a> such as the <a href="/wiki/Falkland_Islands" title="Falkland Islands">Falkland Islands</a>. Moreover, the other parts of the United Kingdom&#160;â Scotland and Northern Ireland&#160;â are foreign countries for present purposes, as are the other <a href="/wiki/British_Islands" title="British Islands">British Islands</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Isle_of_Man" title="Isle of Man">Isle of Man</a>, <a href="/wiki/Jersey" title="Jersey">Jersey</a> and <a href="/wiki/Guernsey" title="Guernsey">Guernsey</a>."</li>
